<DOC><DOCNO> AP881102-0067 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-11-02-88 0450EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-Jews     11-02 0122</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Soviet-Jews,0125</SECOND><HEAD>Number of Jews Allowed to Leave At 8{ Year High</HEAD><DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Jewish emigration from the Soviet Union reached an8{-year high in October, with 2,473 Jews allowed to leave, theorganization involved in their resettlement said today.   Only 78 of the emigres went to Israel after passing through thetransit center at Vienna, said Regina Boucault, spokeswoman for theIntergovernmental Committee for Migration.   She said the Soviets have allowed 14,288 Jews to leave thecountry so far this year, and 1,232 of them have gone to Israel.   The October figure was the highest since March 1980.   The largest official annual exodus _ 51,330 _ was recorded in1979 before the Soviet intervention in Afghanistan chilled East-Westrelations.</TEXT></DOC>